Would love to see greater access for faculty and students to computer resources relevant to the social sciences (e.g. STATA, Qualtrics - on which this survey is designed).

Outlook needs to provide more space. Mailboxes fill up quickly and we spend valuable time deleting emails to make room. Also, the Wifi on campus is unreliable, sometimes cutting out while using web resources in class.

The presentation technology in the classroom is functional and students have internet access for research.  However, I have not seen an upgrade to any classroom equipment during my 10+ years of experience lecturing at FSU. / Many classes still have blackboards and chalk.  I do not get a sense that technology is important from being in the classroom.
We desperately need a campus IT program that fully supports macintosh platforms.

I am sure you are already getting these negative responses.  I will just list the ones that shocked me after coming from two other universities which if I had know how bad it was I would not have come. /  / Wi-Fi is terrible.  It is non-existent without a direct hook up and it is unreliable with a hook up. I didn't even know what was "buffering" until I came to Framingham. /  / The class rooms are not smart with a wire on the floor to hook up your laptop.  It is in every room.  Smart class rooms have smart board technology in the classroom; a performance space that works when your not a Dean or higher; and the Wi-Fi and movies should work.   /  / I was never worried about getting software for students like SPSS or STATA without students paying for it with almost no money they have..  /  / I could write many things... but I will end with one - can we please have the correct time on clocks? /
It would be great if the technology in classrooms worked.
Tried to purc;hase some software for personal computer from start up funds, but still needed IT approval.  Took FOREVER  to get approval. ridiculous
I am only on campus one day a week, therefore, my choices and answers are limited.

My research and teaching increasingly involves analyzing large data sets. I would like to see more resources available on campus (virtual servers or clusters, technical assistance, etc.) to facilitate this work.
My somewhat negative rankings for ITS are influenced by a former employee—the old Mac expert, who was very unhelpful . But he's gone now and has been replaced by someone whom I gather is much better.
In most places of the survey where I chose the 'not applicable' answer, I chose this as the closest option to 'I don't know'.

I was deeply disappointed by the decision to renew the contract with Blackboard Learn against the advice of faculty. The decision and the process both indicated that faculty input was not a particularly important part of the process or the most important consideration (as it should have been).
I would enjoy having IT maintain some server space for a professional web site for professors. The school’s web page is horrendously insufficient in the area of faculty web sites.

For those entering FSU from other institutions outside the State system, MinuteMan is really unwieldy and somewhat archaic to use.  Also, getting a library card for use seems fairly onerous and not clearly explained also.  In fact, I received zero information upon hire and was surprised when I tried to use my ID and discovered it wasn't automatically connected to the library. / More instruction in the features of blackboard would be helpful too.
I am very satisfied with the support at FSU for faculty and students

I am basically satisfied with the library services and online teaching services.  I wish that we had more database access and online journal access, but I understand the limitations of this university. /  / Below is a list of the things that I find difficult to deal with: / 1. myFramingham and DegreeWorks crashing every time we have advising and registration.  Especially during the first week of advising and registration. /  / 2. Approximately once a week, I cannot login to myFramingham, Blackboard, and/or my FSU email because of some odd occurrence that locks me out of the system.  I reported this a number of times during the fall semester.  Also, it is difficult to report this because you cannot open a ticket with the helpdesk without being able to login with your FSU login and password.  If that does not work and you cannot access your email, then how are you supposed to report an issue?  Especially if it is after hours when no one is answering the phone at the helpdesk. /  / 3.  There is ZERO training for how to use the audio/video equipment in the classrooms, and there aren't even any printed guides in the classrooms. /  / 4.  The response to audio/visual issues in classrooms (projector bulb replacement, projector repair, etc.) is SLOW. /  /  /
Robin Robinson is extremely helpful.

faculty need: / 1.speedier accessibility to Blackboard in the classroom.  It's too slow right now for the whole class to do much of anything together.  I think it was much better before moving to the cloud. / 2.more experienced or expert Help Desk staff who focus on the task at hand and don't try to multi-task on other things while my computer is sitting there waiting for their next key input, or constantly have to ask their supervisor for help. / 3.More broadband width in classrooms.  Very difficult to plan to show even a short video clip from the web; can't rely on it for session planning, always have to have a backup plan. /  / On the other hand, tech support for equipment problems while a class is ongoing has gotten a lot better in recent years.  Thank you.
Need MUCH more IT support for training and making content meet accessibility standards.

This is among the worst surveys that I've ever taken.  / 1: It is aggressively long.  / 2: It has no progress bar to give an idea of how much longer it will be.  / 3: It does not give an option to save and continue.  / 4: The questions are often inappropriately asked or will lead to inappropriate data interpretations as asked.  / 5: It implies anonymity without actually providing anonymity.

Because you asked... /  / SPAM and virus protection is weak on campus email and my efforts to create change have been unsuccessful. I receive 10-15 SPAM emails each day and often this number increases to 30-40/day.  I have been made to feel that I am a bother.  Other faculty have just given up on solving this problem. /  / Home access to email is fine. However, I can not include attachments.  No one has been able to tell me why. /  / ETO is extremely responsive, helpful, and knowledgeable. /  / There are rooms in Hemenway Annex that have intermittent wireless outages. /  / When there are classroom tech issues, I don't know who to call. Administrative assistants contact the right person and they come very quickly and rectify the problem. Can't seem to find a direct line. /  / Faculty dashboard is a mess.  I don't know how to personalize it and have never heard that we can. /  / And, while you are asking...This university is in desperate need of a webmaster.  The current 'template' does not meet the needs of the faculty who are trying to recruit students.  The layout doesn't work.  Other university websites are much more inviting and easy to use.  This is absolutely no reflection of the services provided.  It is a poor product.
Retired but now teach online via DGCE - so on-campus training is not possible - very interested in online/virtual classes or tutorials for new things for teaching.

I teach online educator Professional Development courses for K - 12 teachers. All my FSU work is distance learning online courses. The FSU technology dept under the direction of Robin Robinson is excellent support. I receive excellent assistance for my FSU online courses, the group is accessible and highly responsive.
My responses are from a visiting lecturer who is on campus one evening week during the Fall and Spring semesters, and therefore are based on limited use of on-campus resources.

I would like to see more shared computing resources available to faculty (and students). Both my scholarly work and my teaching would be greatly enhanced if I had access to a small server or computer cluster for performing processor-intensive projects.  /  / I currently use my campus-issued laptop for such scholarship-related projects, but processor jobs can take upwards of 12 hours, during which I am unable to use my laptop for other purposes. A dedicated server would allow me to submit jobs that run in the background over longer periods of time.  /  / For student instruction, I currently have students install software on their own laptops. This tends to be problematic due to the large variability in student laptop performance/specs, which leads to a large variability in how the installs are performed. Typically, most students don't have the requisite experience to do the installations entirely on their own, so the process has become quite labor intensive on myself. If students could complete projects on a remote server, this would save a great deal of time. Additionally, it would give students a better feel for how such projects are completed in the real world.  /  / I have discussed the idea of sharing a server with several faculty members on campus from different colleges, but we all agree that we do not have the time or requisite skill set to manage such a resource.
Make your surveys shorter in the future!!

We need server space for our own work and the ability to create local networks in classroom labs so we can have a central and safe location for students to share their work. Let's get in the 21st century already.
We need reliable on campus internet service and a place to back up material.  We still need physical books on campus so the library needs a bigger budget.
I did not even realize we had MyFramingham support available.

ITS support staff are always very nice. One of the biggest challenges is the use of part-time student workers that are NOT experts in IT but are used so that FSU can save money. Laying off full-time qualified IT help and replacing with part-time student workers is a significant mistake that diminishes the professionalism of IT. The student workers are nice but rarely can fix the issue and have to get assistance which makes the interaction take way too long!
We need Qualtrics availability for all interested faculty!

Adjuncts like me receive little support for teaching. Tried to put a book on reserve for my students in a foundation course and was told this was not possible. The Blackboard system is reliable and works for my hybrid class. In room projection systems functioned although the rooms were sometimes too hot to occupy.

RANK_TEXT: Currently adjunct but starting a tenure track position at FSU in September
COMMENT: I really think BlackBoard is terrible. It’s slow and amazingly inefficient. There has to be a better course management system out there.

The library has to join an academic consortium, even if that costs FSU money. The Minuteman network is not primarily academic, and does not serve the institution's mission well at all. More emphasis and resources also need to be placed on building a quality academic physical library collection, and expanding its volume. This move towards thinking of the library as a social space or simply a quiet place to study is misguided. I sometimes get the impression that the library staff are more interested in purging the physical collection of perceived non-useful items than growing it. And the primary purpose of the purging appears to be Library staff wanting to make sure more space isn't taken up by books (creating space for new additions to the collections seems only to be secondary goal), which is a totally unacceptable viewpoint if true. Reference staff in the library are friendly and responsive, but I have seen in other academic libraries reference staff who are much more competent and highly trained to help academic researchers (students and faculty). The new Blackboard seems if anything to be a regression, not an improvement, from the old Blackboard, which was problematic enough.

The most important improvements that could be made are increasing the reliability of classroom technology, increasing hours, number and qualifications of Helpdesk staff, and expanding library database resources.

Would like more tech support people available to come to classrooms in the 8 AM - 8:20 AM range in case some piece of technology is not working in a classroom.  I've had that happen and often a tech shows up 20 minutes into my class.  Since I run a very tight class, content-presentation - wise / workshop-wise, that 20 minute lag time really impacts what I can accomplish in my class.  Please hire some more people to be at the ready first thing in the morning when such issues are usually discovered by us profs teaching in those early slots.  Thanks.
Retired, but work part -time teaching one internship course per semester
Survey too long
The library does not support the business department. That is why my answers have many n/a. My students complain about it.

I am intrigued by the mention of Citation Management Software!  This is a major pain point for my graduate students and we spend semester time to make sure that they can cite properly.  Are there tools on campus to help them with this beyond CASA?  I know that some departments have created their own citing sources 101.  Perhaps we could make a more general one for FSU? /  / Thanks for this survey.  Including a section with links to more information would have been helpful!

In terms of technology, I would like to teach in a classroom that is up to date and equipped with technology already so that I don't have to bring my own laptop to class. The technology in May Hall is completely outdated and impedes my ability to use technology in the classroom. /  / I have been working with librarian Debbie Percher for years now, and she has been a real asset to my students!
Library instruction for students at FSU should be improved.

I worked for a previous sister organization for 18 years. This was Worcester State University (WSU). At WSU if my laptop was sluggish or not performing well, I could bring it to IT. With an appointment, my laptop would be kept overnight and a general "cleaning" or function/performance check was done. I would be provided with a loaner. When I go to IT at FSU, I am given some suggestions or ideas to try to improve function. When I asked about a performance check, the FSU staff has told me it is not available. I think this is a great option and wish the function check was available at FSU.

The staff of the Whittemore Library are to be commended for the extraordinary services and resources they provide given how limited their budget is.  I have found the reference, acquisitions, interlibrary loan, and circulation staff, along with Director Bonnie Mitchell, to be incredibly responsive and helpful. I am particularly thankful to and impressed by Shin Freedman, who is one of FSU's most invaluable and accomplished employees.  The Whittemore Library staff are phenomenal.  I am also highly impressed by and always grateful to the Education technology professionals, especially Stacy Cohen.  Finally, the Help Desk students and the professional staff at ITS have always been available to provide assistance when I have had a printer or laptop concern.

My frustration is lack of tech help on the weekends.  Entering work orders are only worked on quickly during the week.  I haven't found reliable tech help for the weekends.   /  / I would be interested in learning more about online resources and databases through the library. /  /
